  Tumblr   linkedin   stumble   Digg   reddit   Newsvine Permalink http://p.dw.com/p/2vUO1 Slovaks demand sweeping change Protesters denounced Gaspar for failing to crack down on corruption during his time as police chief, and called for a new law that would prevent the interior minister from naming a successor. "The new government hasn't done anything to convince me it will be different than the old government," 38-year-old protester Jan Filip told the Reuters news agency. "Almost all of the cases Kuciak covered could already have been investigated, yet none of them made it to court." Despite Fico's resignation last month, Slovakia's new government under Peter Pellegrini retains several of the same figures from the previous administration. President backs protesters' calls Slovakia's left-leaning President Andrej Kiska, a liberal lawmaker at odds with the country's broad coalition led by left-wing nationalists, echoed calls from the street for Gaspar to step aside. Kiska told Slovakia's TASR news agency that Gaspar's departure was crucial to "rebuilding people's trust in the police." Read more: Murdered Slovak journalist's final report details links between Mafia, government Kuciak's investigations, which were later published posthumously, reported on a deal between the Slovak government and the country's biggest privately owned security firm, whose owner is a relative of Gaspar. Kuciak had also published a series of stories implicating former Interior Minister Robert Kalinak, who appointed Gaspar back in 2012. Kalinak resigned shortly after protesters had begun taking to the streets. The police chief has denied any wrongdoing. Send  Facebook   Twitter   Google+   Whatsapp   
